<h2 id="gma-non-negotiable" style="color:#1565c0;font-size:1.22em;font-weight:650;border-left:4px solid #42a5f5;padding-left:10px;margin-top:1.1em">1. Non-negotiable: hierarchy, numbers, size, and color</h2>

Generated or hand-edited **`.md`** and **`.mdc`** bodies (everything below YAML `---` in `.mdc`) **must** make section levels **instantly distinguishable** in preview: **numeration**, **different effective sizes**, and **different title colors** across levels. Do **not** ship flat walls of same-sized gray `##` headings without an outline and without level styling.

**1 — Outline and body numbering (required for multi-section docs)**

- Include **`## Table of Contents`** / **`## Document outline`** (or equivalent) using a **hierarchical bullet list** of **hyperlinks** only—see [Document outline section](#gma-outline-section). **Do not** prefix TOC rows with a **Markdown ordered-list marker** (`1.`, `2.`, …) when the **link label** already carries the section number (that duplicates numeration). Indent with **`  -`** / **`    -`** for subsections.
- In the **body**, prefer **explicit numbers in major section titles** (e.g. **`## 3. Implementation`**, **`### 3.1 Data model`**) so the doc reads top-to-bottom; numbering lives in the **heading text**, not as a separate TOC list index. Short one-screen notes may omit body numbering **only** if the outline is omitted per the exception below.

**2 — Different sizes (required)**

- Use **at most three levels:** **`#` → `##` → `###`**. Never fake depth with bold lines instead of real headings.
- **`#`** = document title (one per file, largest). **`##`** = major sections (clearly smaller than `#`). **`###`** = subsections (clearly smaller than `##`). Do not skip levels for the same conceptual depth.

**3 — Different font colors for section titles (required in Cursor-rich previews)**

- Default Markdown **`#` / `##` / `###`** does **not** set custom colors—renderers pick one neutral palette. For **visible color differentiation between levels**, use **HTML headings** with inline `style` **or** the **portable palette** below.

- **Portable default palette** (subtle, high-contrast blues/teals—reuse for every doc unless the repo defines its own):

```html
<h1 id="doc-title" style="color:#0d47a1;font-size:1.5em;font-weight:700;border-bottom:2px solid #90caf9;padding-bottom:0.25em;margin-top:0">Document title</h1>

<h2 id="major-section" style="color:#1565c0;font-size:1.22em;font-weight:650;border-left:4px solid #42a5f5;padding-left:10px;margin-top:1.1em">2. Major section</h2>

<h3 id="subsection" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1.05em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.85em">3.1 Subsection</h3>
```

- **Rules:** set matching **`id="..."`** on every HTML heading used in the outline links; **one palette per file**; do not rainbow-tint body paragraphs—**titles only** unless a callout pattern is documented in-repo.

**4 — `.mdc` rule files**

- After frontmatter, treat the body like any other Markdown spec: **`## Document outline`** first (**bullet** hyperlink TOC per [§3](#gma-outline-section)), then body sections using **number + HTML color/size** so long rules remain scannable in Cursor.

**Exception:** A trivial one-screen note may skip the outline and optional HTML headings; **default** is full hierarchy + outline for anything longer or multi-topic.

