<h2 id="gma-visual-aids" style="color:#1565c0;font-size:1.22em;font-weight:650;border-left:4px solid #42a5f5;padding-left:10px;margin-top:1.1em">6. Visual aids: tables and Mermaid</h2>

Use **HTML tables** and **Mermaid** when they clarify structure—**not** in every doc. Follow **[6.1](#gma-tables)** and **[6.2](#gma-mermaid)** so visuals stay consistent within a file or doc set.

<h3 id="gma-tables" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1.05em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.85em">6.1 HTML comparison tables</h3>

Use this pattern for comparison and option tables so they stay consistent and easy to scan.

<h4 id="gma-table-visual" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.75em">6.1.1 Visual and layout</h4>

- **Header row:** Dark blue background, white text (`background:#1565c0;color:white`).
- **Column headers:** Clear labels; add a small subtitle in `<small>` where helpful (e.g. "where code lives", "where it deploys").
- **Body rows:** Alternating or strategy-specific background colors (e.g. green `#e8f5e9`, amber `#fff3e0`, red tint `#ffebee`).
- **Aspect / left column:** Light blue `#e3f2fd` for the "Aspect" or "Strategy" column so it stands out.

<h4 id="gma-table-text" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.75em">6.1.2 Text and structure</h4>

- **Numeration:** Use ① ② ③ (or 1. 2. 3.) for strategies, options, or aspects.
- **Bullets:** Use `•` and `<br>` to break multi-item content into short lines.
- **Badges:**
  - <span style="background:#c8e6c9;padding:2px 4px">✓</span> (green) for pros / advantages / "yes".
  - <span style="background:#ffcdd2;padding:2px 4px">⚠</span> (red) for cons / risks / warnings.
  - <span style="background:#fff9c4;padding:2px 4px">manual</span> (yellow) for manual steps.
  - <span style="background:#c8e6c9;padding:2px 4px">auto</span> (green) for automatic.
- **Inline labels:** Use short colored spans to distinguish concepts (e.g. <span style="background:#e3f2fd;padding:1px 3px">branch</span> vs <span style="background:#fff3e0;padding:1px 3px">env</span> for source branch vs target environment).
- **Recommendation:** Use a small badge like <span style="background:#2e7d32;color:white;padding:1px 4px">recommended</span> for the preferred option.

<h4 id="gma-table-distinguish" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.75em">6.1.3 Distinguishing concepts</h4>

- When the table mixes **source** (e.g. Git branch, config file) and **target** (e.g. deployment environment):
  - Add a **legend** above the table: e.g. "**Source branch** = Git branch (where code lives). **Target env** = deployment environment (dev, staging, prod)."
  - Use **column headers** that say "Source branch(es)" and "Target env (deploy trigger)" (or similar).
  - In cells, use inline labels (e.g. "branch <code>main</code> → env dev") so branch vs env are visually distinct.

<h4 id="gma-table-exemplar" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.75em">6.1.4 Exemplar (minimal table)</h4>

Self-contained example (generic criteria × options); copy the pattern, not the cell text.

<table>
<thead>
<tr style="background:#1565c0;color:white"><th>Aspect</th><th>Option A</th><th>Option B</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td style="background:#e3f2fd">Latency</td><td style="background:#e8f5e9">low</td><td style="background:#fff3e0">higher</td></tr>
<tr><td style="background:#e3f2fd">Operate cost</td><td style="background:#fff3e0">lower</td><td style="background:#e8f5e9">higher</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3 id="gma-mermaid" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1.05em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.85em">6.2 Mermaid diagrams</h3>

Use this style for Mermaid in documentation so diagrams stay consistent, colorful, and easy to read (including in Cursor preview). Example node labels below are **illustrative**—replace with your domain.

<h4 id="gma-mermaid-layout" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.75em">6.2.1 Layout</h4>

- Prefer **simple flows**:
  - `graph TD` for top-down flows (e.g. release steps).
  - `graph LR` for left-to-right flows (e.g. data paths).
- Keep diagrams focused:
  - 5–11 nodes per diagram is ideal.
  - Use multiple diagrams instead of one huge one when needed.
- For long labels, use `\n` to break lines inside a node (e.g. `Deploy\nto staging`).

<h4 id="gma-mermaid-colors" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.75em">6.2.2 Colors and shapes</h4>

- Reuse the following **semantic** color mapping (adapt node labels to your domain):
  - **Blue (`#e3f2fd` + `#1976d2`):** Sources / triggers (e.g. PRs, branches, orchestration entry).
  - **Orange/amber (`#fff3e0` / `#fff8e1` + `#e65100` / `#ff8f00`):** CI / decision points.
  - **Green (`#e8f5e9` + `#2e7d32`):** Successful steps and verification.
  - **Purple (`#ede7f6` + `#5e35b1`):** Staging / intermediate environments.
  - **Red/pink (`#ffebee` + `#c62828`):** Production, approval, or high-risk steps.
- Use consistent node shapes:
  - Rectangles for actions.
  - Diamonds for decisions (e.g. `{Merge}`).

<h4 id="gma-mermaid-font" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.75em">6.2.3 Font and sizing</h4>

- Use **`font-size:9px`** for all diagram `style` lines (balances readability with density):
  - Example: `style A fill:#e3f2fd,stroke:#1976d2,stroke-width:1px,font-size:9px`
- Use **`stroke-width:1px`** consistently across diagrams in the same document (or doc set).

<h4 id="gma-mermaid-snippets" style="color:#00695c;font-size:1em;font-weight:600;margin-top:0.75em">6.2.4 Style snippets</h4>

**Illustrative** flow (CI/CD-shaped labels); replace nodes with your own domain (e.g. ingest → transform → store).

```mermaid
graph TD
  A[PR to main] --> B[CI: lint, unit tests]
  B --> C{Merge}
  C --> D[Deploy to dev]
  D --> E[Verify dev]

  style A fill:#e3f2fd,stroke:#1976d2,stroke-width:1px,font-size:9px
  style B fill:#fff3e0,stroke:#e65100,stroke-width:1px,font-size:9px
  style C fill:#fff8e1,stroke:#ff8f00,stroke-width:1px,font-size:9px
  style D fill:#e8f5e9,stroke:#2e7d32,stroke-width:1px,font-size:9px
  style E fill:#e8f5e9,stroke:#2e7d32,stroke-width:1px,font-size:9px
```

